         <div type="transcription">
            <p>
<lb corresp="#a3"/><gap reason="lost"/><gap reason="plain" quantity="1"/><gap reason="lost"/>
<lb corresp="#a4"/><gap reason="lost"/><w><supplied>sa</supplied>hāye</w><gap reason="lost"/>
<lb corresp="#a5"/><gap reason="lost"/><w><supplied>ku</supplied>lypalaṃ</w><w>ñäkcyāñ</w><gap reason="lost"/>
<lb corresp="#a6"/><gap reason="lost"/><w>ṣinās</w><w>poränyo</w><gap reason="lost"/>
<lb corresp="#b1"/><gap reason="lost"/><w>ak<supplied>a</supplied>ppiṣi</w><w>lyä<supplied>m</supplied></w><gap reason="lost"/>
<lb corresp="#b2"/><gap reason="lost"/><w><supplied>wä</supplied>rtāṣimār</w><pc>:</pc><w><gap reason="plain" unit="part"/>l<gap reason="plain" unit="part"/></w><gap reason="lost"/>
<lb corresp="#b3"/><gap reason="lost"/><w><gap reason="plain" unit="part"/>ā</w><gap reason="plain" quantity="1"/><w>swār</w><w>ñi</w><gap reason="lost"/>
<lb corresp="#b4"/><gap reason="lost"/><gap reason="plain" quantity="1"/><gap reason="lost"/></p>
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... companion ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... to be desired divine ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... (burnt) by the fires of ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... the lake of impurity ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... may I throw. ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... sweet ... for me (?) ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">...</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="remarks">An effaced vertical black line at the end of the top line of the recto and the bottom line of the verso is tentatively taken as an indication of the string hole (see <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht1137"/>). This is the basis for the line numbering.</note><note corresp="#a6" type="philcomment">: cf. <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-a220"/> a5 <hi>onmīṣinās poränyo</hi>, <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-a377"/> a4 <hi>kleśāṣinās poräṃ</hi>.</note><note corresp="#b2" type="philcomment"><hi>/// (wä)rtāṣimār</hi>: this is one of the very few possibilities, perhaps the only one, for a 1sg.opt.mid. to a causative verb to a root in <hi>-rt</hi>. This is without doubt the form <hi>tāṣimār</hi> cited as an opt. to <hi>täs-</hi> 'put' by <bibl><title corresp="ref:siegetal1931"/><citedRange>438</citedRange></bibl>. As I have argued, this is morphologically not possible (<bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2013b"/><citedRange>430</citedRange></bibl>).</note></p>
         </div>
